{"text": "Iran has entered a state of survival following the death of Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei in a series of targeted airstrikes. The 86-year-old cleric was killed after decades of trading threats and missiles with Israel and the United States. Satellite imagery confirms the destruction of his secure compound in downtown Tehran, now reduced to a grey mass. While the strike marks the end of an era for a nation that has known only one leader for 40 years, the Islamic Republic's system of rule remains functional. Security has been tightened across major cities as volunteer paramilitaries and armed police patrol the streets to prevent potential uprisings. Despite calls from the West for a popular revolt, ordinary Iranians appear to be prioritizing safety over civil unrest. For now, a temporary council consisting of the heads of the judiciary, legislature, and executive will govern the country according to the constitution. Experts suggest the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps is poised to seize even greater political and economic influence during this transition. The leadership vacuum also raises urgent questions regarding Iran's nuclear policy and its long-standing religious edict against weaponization. With Khamenei gone, internal voices seeking greater flexibility in the country's pursuit of deterrence may finally gain traction. Internationally, the assassination has drawn sharp condemnation from China and Russia, while the region braces for the seismic consequences of this power shift. Khamenei's legacy will ultimately be defined by his iron fist and a four-decade fixation on challenging Western interests.", "language": "", "model": "parakeet-nvidia/parakeet-tdt-0.6b-v3", "duration": 90, "segments": {"word": [{"word": "Iran", "start_offset": 0, "end_offset": 7, "start": 0.0, "end": 0.56}, {"word": "has", "start_offset": 7, "end_offset": 9, "start": 0.56, "end": 0.72}, {"word": "entered", "start_offset": 9, "end_offset": 13, "start": 0.72, "end": 1.04},